metadata.name: Zee  #3
metadata.description:
As wild as it is, for me the sea has something soothing. The rushing of the waves, the strong wind in your face, the salty air, the screeching of seagulls, freezing rain. At the coast it is easy to forget everything and be in the moment. The view is expansive and no matter how ominous the clouds, somewhere the sun breaks through. 

At the same time, the raging sea can be life-threatening. Many have lost their lives at sea or by the sea, some by flooding, some in the battle for peace, others in search of a better life. 

The sea, with its many faces and stories, is beautiful, terrifying and everything in between. 

#Features
Are there birds, and if so, how many?
Is it raining?
How cloudy is it?
How rough is the sea?

Generative art coded with p5js.

metadata.description:

It finishes when the canvas has been fully covered. There are 20 color palettes inspired by natural phenomena. It was programmed from scratch in vanilla JavaScript.

metadata.name: gradient descent #131
metadata.description:
Whether by choice or circumstance, we often find our lives thrust into uncertainty. We're resilient, though — we find patterns in the chaos, deciphering and unraveling it piece by piece until a new comfort emerges. `gradient descent` is my expression of that cyclical flow that comes to dominate our lives.

The piece starts with comfort, a smooth gradient chosen from a curated palette. As the animation runs, that gradient is mutated by a unique sequence of linear transformations - slice, skew or stride on an underlying grid - as it descends into uncertainty. After a time the animation will reverse, peeling back each transformation and returning to comfort before beginning anew.

The menu - which can be accessed with a double click or Escape - gives you extensive control of the experience. I'd encourage you to explore these settings — they transform the feel of the piece, allowing you to adapt it to match your environment or mood. Any setting that can be changed in the menu can also be provided as a URL parameter - there's a button in the menu to export them all.

Built with raw WebGL 1.0, optimised to run smoothly on most devices.

Best viewed in full screen on large format displays.

||| controls

[hold space] ⇝ speed up
[esc/2xclick] ⇝ toggle menu
[g] ⇝ toggle gallery mode
[p] ⇝ toggle pause
[s] ⇝ capture current frame
[a] ⇝ capture all keyframes
[8/9/0/-] ⇝ change viewport

||| settings

All settings are configurable via the interactive menu. Initial values can be set as url parameters by adding &[name]=[value] to the url.

loop [1|0, default 1]
|  ⇝  loop the animation
infinite [1|0, default 0]
|  ⇝  generate a new sequence after each descent, constantly evolving
gallery [1|0, default 0]
|  ⇝  display in gallery mode with keyframes
quality [#, default 1]
|  ⇝  additional dpr scaling - lower to improve animation smoothness
speed [#, default 1]
|  ⇝  multiplier for step animation speed
step-pause [#, default 0.35]
|  ⇝  seconds to pause between keyframe steps
start-pause [#, default 4]
|  ⇝  seconds to pause at the initial keyframe
end-pause [#, default 4]
|  ⇝  seconds to pause at the final keyframe

||| capture

Capture current frame saves the still immediately, while capture all keyframes saves each of the keyframes sequentially. Some browsers may require confirmation to save multiple stills. When triggered early, unrendered keyframes will be blank. All captures are impacted by the following settings.

capture-aspect [#, default 1]
|  ⇝  aspect ratio of the capture, as width/height
capture-size [#, default 2048]
|  ⇝  longest dimension of the captures to save, in pixels

metadata.name: Sweeping #11
metadata.description:
Sweeping is a piece in which I explore the uses of noise fields. Using them in the most cliche way possible, but trying to make something unique out of that.

What started out as an innocent weekend project grew out to be quite the piece, which is why I am publishing it here.



Sweeping uses the GPU of your machine for its shading, which means it won't run particularly well on mobile devices. My recommended way of viewing this piece is on a PC with a dedicated GPU.

metadata.name: Subjective photography #1 #7
metadata.description:
Inspired by the Subjective Photography artistic movement born in the 40s in Germany, this project seeks to achieve visual abstraction trough photography. In Subjective Photography, form prevails representation. So with this work we emulated the analogical results that those experimental photographers did on the darkroom merging films, this time with digital photography and coding. 

The idea behind this project was to blend organic shapes found on nature with mathematical patterns present on architecture, framed on the three basic geometric shapes resulting on abstract and intriguing pictures.

Dive into this darkroom and develop unique pictures.

Press “s” key to download a high resolution .png image.

Coded with p5.js by josemiguel.tez (José Ramirez Guaigua)
Photographies made by vocesferales (Lorena Orlando)
Coded and photographed on August 2022.

metadata.name: <iframes> #314
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: "Alphabetic signs" - (MatrixV2) #63
metadata.description:
Alphabetic signs on canvas. 
Alphabetic signs in a matrix. 

The "Alphabetic Signs" series finds its roots in different places: in my physical work, in a study on letters and typefaces, but also in graffiti and street art.

Through Generative Art, I sought to give continuity to the style my physical pieces by connecting two worlds: the “old” world of material paintings, and the new world of algorithm-generated art. Generative art has allowed me to create many more combinations by introducing greater variability in the elements.

In this project, the alphabetic signs were forced into a matrix to give order to the chaos produced by the pseudo-random composition of alphabetic signs. I wrote the Javascript code to compose 31 different alphabetic elements, which include the 26 letters of the Latin alphabet. Each alphabetic element is coded to adapt to different areas on the canvas, tightening, stretching and expanding.

This work uses p5.js library.

metadata.name: TRQ.1 #23
metadata.description:
The aesthetics of the work is inspired by the work of the Brazilian artist DIONISIO DEL SANTO, above all, the formal simplification, the use of geometric figures, in addition to planes and colors, in a simplified way, the work also makes reference to the principles of Concretism, as a movement artistic.

Features:
PALETTES
In total, the work has fifteen different color palettes, with percentages of probability of occurrence varying between 2% and 15%.

FORMES
The images are structured using only three simple shapes (square, rectangle and triangle) proportional to each other. Said shapes can also be rotated and interleaved with empty squares.
The use of each one of the forms follows three different combination patterns, according to the description and percentages of occurrence indicated below:
“+++” – 50% | full square + triangle
“++” – 35% | rectangle + triangle
“+” – 15% | just triangle

INVERSÉ
One of the rare features, with only a 10% probability, is the occurrence of the inverted color palette, in which the colors of the background, simple shapes and frame, are put in negative.

VECTEUR
The background was structured following two possible direction vectors (horizontal – 40% or vertical – 60%).

MODULES
The canvas can be subdivided following three different modulations, which can be 3X3 (20% chance), 4X4 (45% chance) or 5X5 (35% chance).

September 01, 2022.
Generative token by Paivei made with p5js for FxHash.

metadata.name: Five-Leaf-Flowers #5
metadata.description:
'Five-Leaf-Flowers' is a reinterpretation and development of the most popular symbol story of good luck and financial well-being - the five-leaf clover; transferring it from the world of things to the world of ideas, with incommensurably greater opportunities for growth and revealing the true potential.

In the real world, there is a one in 25,000 chance to find a five-leaf clover, to meet one of 95 Five-Leaf-Flowers on Web3 will soon become quite a good luck ;)

Press [S] in live mode to save a piece of luck with high-resolution.
